class Solution {
public:
    /*
    Algorithm- 
    We will rearrange the array such that each `valid` element get its correct place and then search for the answer in rearranged array.

    Question-0: Why the thought of array rearrangement should click OR Why this method?
        We can easily solve this question using unordered_set but that will cost us O(n) space and we are expected to solve it in O(1) extra space hence
		we have to somehow make use of existing space to get the answer and hence the thought of array rearrangment should click.

    Question-1: What is correct the place for an element in the rearranged array? 
        For an element i its correct place is i-1 th index in the array.
        E.g. [5,3,4,1,2] -> [1,2,3,4,5] or [4,-2,5,3,0] -> [0,-2,3,4,5].

    Question-2: Which elements will not get its correct place OR which are `invalid` elements? 
        1. Elements which are non-positive -> We do not have any index in the array to store them(Hence condition-1: nums[i] <= 0 then continue).
        2. If element is larger than array size -> We again do not have correct index to store such elements(Hence condition-2: nums[i] > sz then continue). 
        3. Repeated elements -> As one index can hold only one correct element other repeated elements will have to be ignored (Hence condition-3: 
		   nums[nums[i]-1] == nums[i] means element with which we are swapping current element is already in its correct position so ignore).

    Question-3: How we will get the final answer?
        We will go through the modified array and find the first position(in or outside the array) which does not hold the correct element.
    */
    int firstMissingPositive(vector<int>& nums) {
        int sz = nums.size();
        for(int i=0;i<sz;i++) {
            while(nums[i] != i+1) {
                if(nums[i] <= 0 || nums[i] > sz || nums[nums[i]-1] == nums[i]) break;
                swap(nums[nums[i]-1], nums[i]);
            }
        }
        for(int i=0;i<sz;i++) if(nums[i] != i+1) return i+1;
        return sz+1;
    }
};
```

